The younger generation, born in the 21st century, may be the last pure appreciators of art and the last ones to establish a genuine connection with artists, as they are not burdened with the pressure of viewing everything through a critical, colored lens.
We grew up in the golden age of media, when people shared a common understanding of popular culture, but now this collective consciousness has disappeared.
In those days, we didn't have to worry about the source of the content and could immerse ourselves directly, because in that era, tracing the roots was not easy.
We revered these artists as deities and had no reason to question such adoration. As a result, a "quasi-social relationship" was formed between us and them, which we considered an indispensable part of life.
This also explains why we are so enamored with nostalgia.
We would watch "The Office" together with our friends every Thursday, having pizza while doing so.
This experience is in stark contrast to our current experience of watching TV shows through streaming services. Streaming platforms typically release 12 episodes at once, allowing each person to watch at their own pace, while also posting spoiler warnings on social media or confining discussions to specific groups.
We all secretly yearn to relive the collective sense of belonging that connected everyone.
It's precisely because of the nostalgia factor at play that we keep revisiting TV shows like "The Office" or movies like "The King of Comedy", with those unforgettable catchphrases spreading like memes online.
We often quote these iconic lines from the works and assume that most people will understand the reference.
Even if something goes viral online, we can't assume everyone has seen it.
With the current pace of information explosion, there's simply too much to keep track of – let alone sift through – and the question remains: will we ever be able to break free from this information overload?
We keep discovering new media and new artists, only to find out they're either serial abusers or spewing hateful ideologies, and the cycle continues, becoming increasingly tiresome.
We're torn between indulging in nostalgia and acknowledging that the creators of the art we cherish may have had serious moral flaws, leaving us feeling lost and uncertain.
We will establish a "quasi-social relationship" with artists even more cautiously.
We gradually realize that one who seeks wealth and power may find it difficult to guarantee that they won't harm or exploit others.
Due to the disappearance of the collective media consciousness, we've developed a class consciousness that helps us maintain critical thinking.
Some people are still obstinately nostalgic, elevating others to pedestals, only to feign shock when their idols collapse.
We're living in a transformative era, and I'm eager to know which path we'll take.
Inclusivity and safety should be the defaults.
